Using Artifacts
Plugins can distribute MCP server binaries via Azure Artifacts feeds using agency artifact exec. This command works like npx — it downloads the artifact on first use, caches it locally, and runs a binary from within it. Stdin/stdout/stderr pass through transparently, making it ideal for stdio-based MCP servers.

How It Works
In your plugin's MCP config (agent frontmatter mcp_servers, .vscode/mcp.json, or ~/.copilot/mcp-config.json), specify agency as the command with artifact exec arguments:

{
  "mcpServers": {
    "my-mcp": {
      "type": "stdio",
      "command": "agency",
      "args": [
        "artifact", "exec",
        "--feed", "https://pkgs.dev.azure.com/myorg/MyProject/_packaging/MyFeed/upack/download",
        "--name", "my-mcp-server",
        "--version", "1.0.0",
        "--", "my-mcp-server", "--stdio"
      ]
    }
  }
}
When the engine spawns this MCP server, Agency:

Resolves the package name with a platform suffix (e.g., my-mcp-server.win-x64 on Windows)
Checks the local cache (~/.agency/artifacts/cli/my-mcp-server.{rid}/{version}/)
Downloads the artifact from the ADO feed if that version is not cached
Resolves my-mcp-server inside the artifact directory (appending .exe on Windows automatically)
Executes it with stdin/stdout pass-through
Cross-Platform Support
agency artifact exec is designed to work identically across Windows, macOS, and Linux with zero config changes:

Automatic platform package selection (--rid auto): By default, --rid auto appends the current platform's Runtime Identifier to --name. For example, --name my-mcp-server becomes:

Platform	Resolved package name
Windows x64	my-mcp-server.win-x64
Windows ARM64	my-mcp-server.win-arm64
macOS ARM64	my-mcp-server.osx-arm64
macOS x64	my-mcp-server.osx-x64
Linux x64	my-mcp-server.linux-x64
Linux ARM64	my-mcp-server.linux-arm64
This means the same MCP config works everywhere — just publish platform-specific packages with the .{rid} suffix.

Automatic binary name resolution: The command after -- is resolved with platform awareness:

On Windows: my-server automatically finds my-server.exe
On Linux/macOS: my-server.exe automatically finds my-server (without extension)
Opting out: Use --rid none to use the exact --name without any platform suffix, or --rid win-x64 to force a specific platform.

CLI Reference
# Download an artifact to the local cache
agency artifact download --feed <URL> --name <NAME> [--version <VERSION>] [--rid auto|none|<RID>]

# Download (if needed) and execute a binary from an artifact
agency artifact exec --feed <URL> --name <NAME> [--version <VERSION>] [--rid auto|none|<RID>] -- <COMMAND> [ARGS...]
Option	Required	Default	Description
--feed	Yes	—	Azure Artifacts feed URL
--name	Yes	—	Base package name (platform suffix appended by --rid)
--version	No	latest	Package version (omit for latest)
--type	No	universal	universal or nuget
--rid	No	auto	Platform suffix: auto (detect), none (exact name), or explicit RID
--output	No	~/.agency/artifacts/cli/{name}.{rid}/{version}/	Download directory (download only). When specified, this exact path is used.
Publishing MCP Server Binaries
Publish platform-specific packages with the .{rid} suffix so --rid auto resolves correctly:

As Universal Packages (one per platform):

# Build for each platform, then publish each:
az artifacts universal publish \
  --organization https://dev.azure.com/myorg \
  --project MyProject --scope project \
  --feed MyFeed \
  --name my-mcp-server.win-x64 \
  --version 1.0.0 \
  --path ./dist/win-x64/

az artifacts universal publish \
  --organization https://dev.azure.com/myorg \
  --project MyProject --scope project \
  --feed MyFeed \
  --name my-mcp-server.linux-x64 \
  --version 1.0.0 \
  --path ./dist/linux-x64/
As NuGet packages:

Create a .nuspec per platform (e.g., My.Mcp.Server.win-x64.nuspec).
Run nuget pack to create the .nupkg.
Push to your ADO feed.
See Plugin Artifacts for full details on feed URL format and authentication.